node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / After exploring Kate’s Cove cave during the Greenland Caves Project's 2019 expedition, we headed back over to Grottedalen to look at some potential caves that we thought we could see through binoculars during our 2015 expedition. Back then, they were tiny black dots in the distance—too far away to tell if they were shadows or not and too far away to reach on foot. This time, with the advantage of a helicopter, we were able to cover a lot more ground. Pictured here is the icy entrance to Crystal Kingdom, one of the most northerly explored caves on the planet.

node.text: Photo by @mattborowick / The Arkansas River flows through Royal Gorge just outside of Cañon City, Colorado. The gorge is 1,250 feet (381 meters) deep. I always get a little nervous standing close to the edge to get pictures like this, but it's always worth it in the end. Please follow @mattborowick for more pictures like this. #colorado #mountains #nature #adventure #royalgorge

node.text:
Photos by @dina_litovsky / Since last summer I have been documenting the way New York City's streets have been transformed since the pandemic. The addition of outdoor dining has been a joy to witness as the metropolis stubbornly plows through the recovery phase. No weather, no virus, nothing will stop New Yorkers from dining out. And with people-watching an added bonus, New York City’s street life has become impossibly more vibrant. 
For more photos, follow me @dina_litovsky.

node.text: Photo by @kiliiiyuyan / Evening light illuminates the trunks of trees long dead from saltwater intrusion on a marsh in the Skagit Valley in Washington State. This saltwater estuary is invaluable for numerous species of animals including juvenile fish, and it’s one of the fastest declining ecosystems globally. Several pairs of bald eagles make their nests in this slough. #wileyslough #salishsea #landscape

node.text: Photo by @MichaelGeorge / The conservatory at the New York Botanical Garden is a sight to behold. It is larger than it appears and houses everything from a sea of orchids to a staghorn fern the size of a small boulder. The glass structure was completed in 1902 and has undergone several restorations since then. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #nybg #newyorkbotanicgarden #plantconservatory #plants #orchids

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / During our 2019 Greenland Caves Project expedition to northeastern Greenland, Kate’s Cove cave (pictured) was first spotted by Paul Smith and our helicopter pilot, Stig-Erick, during the initial mobilization to Camp 1. But we didn’t get to explore it until we moved to Camp 2. The whole team was very excited because we’d heard great things about this big entrance filled with ice. We were not disappointed. The cave turned out to be our longest discovered cave this year. At 104 meters (341 feet) in length, it is the longest explored cave in Greenland.

node.text:
Video by @bertiegregory / A pod of common dolphins blast along 30 miles (48 kilometers) off the coast of Wales. After seeing these dolphins fly out of the water at high speed, I assumed they were on the hunt. However, I soon realized they weren’t after food; the dolphins were in a mating frenzy. For an hour they ripped around chasing each other, periodically forming balls for PG-13 activities. 
Follow @bertiegregory for more wildlife adventures. #dolphin #ocean #sea #britishwildlife #drone

Photographer @amivitale captured this video in the Namunyak Wildlife Conservancy at @sararafoundation in northern Kenya. In the 1990s elephant populations here were poached to near local extinction. Thanks to community-based conservation, elephants and other wildlife have made an extraordinary comeback. Today, there are more than 8,700 elephants in the area, making it Kenya's second largest population of elephants! Nature is resilient when we give it a chance and make it a priority.
Follow @amivitale and @sararafoundation to learn more, including how you can help. @kenyawildlifeservice @thephotosociety #protectelephants #elephants #stoppoaching #kenya #empathyiseverything
